The paper deals with distributed algorithms for optimization problems on network graphs, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The algorithms rely on the mixing time of the network graph, which is a property studied in the context of random graphs and falls under the category of Discrete Mathematics (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the practical implications of the algorithms for peer-to-peer and overlay networks, which falls under the category of Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NE). The paper uses techniques from information theory and probability theory to analyze the algorithms, which falls under the category of Information Theory (cs.IT) and Machine Learning (cs.LG).
